    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait what? what is a goblin's whispering walls? i dont get the analogy. can u just explain it without the goblin stuff? i just need to understand the physics part for my exam.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let me try to simplify it for you.\n\nIn classical physics, correlation between two particles means that if one particle's state changes, the other particle's state will change in a predictable way. For example, if you flip a coin, the other coin will either be heads or tails, depending on the first coin. This is a deterministic relationship, where the state of one particle directly affects the state of the other.\n\nIn contrast, quantum entanglement is a non-deterministic correlation. When two particles are entangled, their properties are connected in a way that can't be explained by classical physics. Measuring the state of one particle will instantly affect the state of the other particle, regardless of the distance between them. This effect happens even if they're separated by billions of kilometers.\n\nThink of it like a game of \"cause-and-effect\" where the cause (measuring one particle) affects the effect (the other particle) instantly, but the relationship between the two is not directly causal. It's more like a... well, I suppose I'll just have to find a different analogy that doesn't involve goblins!",
